          "body": "Zechariah 14 is the book's final word, and it earns its position. The chapter opens at the lowest point — Jerusalem besieged, plundered, women ravished, half the population exiled (14:1-2) — and ends at the highest conceivable point: horses bearing 'HOLY TO THE LORD' and every cooking pot in the city consecrated to the LORD of hosts (14:20-21). The movement is not random. It follows the pattern of the exodus itself: maximum darkness before the divine dawn, maximum human helplessness before the divine act, the humiliation of God's enemies before the exaltation of God's name. Zechariah is not writing history; he is writing eschatology shaped by the grammar of Israel's past redemptions. This is why the chapter is simultaneously recognizable (Jerusalem, the Mount of Olives, the Feast of Booths) and world-shattering in its cosmic claims."
